2 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Qualifications of commissioners. At the time of the appointment and
3 throughout the Article V convention, a commissioner:
4 (1) must be a United States citizen for at least 10 years prior to appointment;
5 (2) must be a resident of the state for at least 5 years prior to appointment;
6 (3) must be at least 25 18 years old;
7 (4) must be a registered voter in the state;
8 (5) may not have been registered as or required to be registered as a federal lobbyist at any time
9 within the past 5 years;
10 (6) may not have been a federal employee (other than a member of the United States armed
11 forces) or a federal contractor at any time within the past 10 years;
12 (7) may not have held a federal elected or appointed office at any time within the past 10 years;
13 (8) may not have had a felony conviction for a crime involving moral turpitude in any jurisdiction or
14 a felony conviction for any crime in any jurisdiction within the past 10 years; and
15 (9) may not hold a statewide office while performing the duties of commissioner. For the purposes
16 of this section, a position as a state legislator is not considered a "statewide office".
17
18 NEW SECTION. Section 4. Commissioner selection and removal. (1) Commissioners must be
19 named by a resolution passed by a majority of those present and voting in a joint session of the legislature. All
20 commissioners must be appointed by this process.
21 (2) The legislature shall maintain an odd number of commissioners in the delegation.
22 (3) (a) A commissioner or a delegation may be recalled or removed at any time and for any reason
23 by a joint resolution of the legislature or by a majority of those present and voting in a joint session of the
24 legislature.
25 (b) If the legislature is not in session, a commissioner or a delegation may be recalled and
26 suspended from duty by the advisory committee, pending a vote of the legislature.
